{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489621"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:23:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:23:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/705"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.72,0.09,0.03,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28655"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"430"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of pain in the right eye, blurring of vision and a constant frontal headache. She has ongoing nausea and has vomited once since her symptoms started. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medication. She wears glasses for reading. On examination, the left eye is normal. The right eye is red, with a hazy cornea and a mid-dilated pupil which does not react to light. Her visual acuity is normal in the left eye, however she can only identify hand movements at one metre in the right eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical prednisolone","Intravenous acetazolamide","Topical tropicamide","Oral metoprolol","Intravenous hydrocortisone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a classical presentation of acute angle-closure glaucoma (AACG), characterised by the history of headache, vomiting, and unilateral visual blurring. Key examination findings are a hazy cornea and a fixed mid-dilated (or mid-position) pupil, meaning an irregularly semi-dilated pupil which is not reactive to light. AACG occurs due to occlusion of the anterior chamber angle most commonly by apposition of the posterior iris with the lens, thus preventing aqueous drainage and causing increased intraocular pressure. Risk factors include hyperopia, increased age, female gender and east asian descent. This is an ophthalmological emergency, as permanent damage to the optic nerve can occur within hours due to ischemia secondary to uncontrolled intraocular pressures. This patient needs urgent treatment and ophthalmological consultation for definitive treatment (which is YAG laser iridotomy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor and is used in the emergency treatment of AACG due to its effect of decreasing production of aqueous humour. Oral acetazolamide is an appropriate alternative if \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous acetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is unavailable. Other emergency treatments include use of beta blockers, prostaglandin analogues, alpha-2-agonists, carbonic anhydrase inhibitors, and consideration of intravenous mannitol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is occasionally used in the treatment of AACG, however should only be prescribed by an ophthalmologist after review as they can increase intraocular pressure and thus exacerbate glaucoma in some patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical tropicamide\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in AACG as it causes further pupillary block and worsens angle-closure. All topical mydriatic agents should be avoided in the setting of AACG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metoprolol \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated in this patient - however topical (not systemic) beta blockers such as timolol may be used to treat AACG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the treatment of AACG, and can precipitate or exacerbate episodes. An important differential to exclude is giant cell arteritis (in which case intravenous steroids are crucial to treatment), however GCA more commonly presents with an acute complete loss of vision, scalp or temple tenderness and jaw claudication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intravenous acetazolamide is the first-line treatment for acute angle-closure glaucoma."],"references":["Murray D. Emergency management: angle-closure glaucoma. Community Eye Health. 2018;31(103):64. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6253313/","Ehlers JP, Shah CP. The Wills eye manual: Office and emergency room diagnosis and treatment of eye disease. Philadelphia: Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2016"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28655"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28655"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-25T11:15:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-25T11:15:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"705"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/430"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Glaucoma","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T11:31:33+10:30"},"relationshi